{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489130"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"599"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/599"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.41,0.09,0.3,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51910"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/599"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37211"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"472"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15409"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51910"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of a rash on both shins. He has also had increasing fatigue over the last four months. He has a medical history of Child\u0027s C liver cirrhosis, alcohol dependence and untreated hepatitis C. He does not take any regular medications. He continues to drink six beers daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The rash is bilateral, located anteriorly on the lower legs and petechial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal normal full blood count and renal function. A biopsy of the skin lesions shows small vessel inflammation with immune deposits in the vascular walls.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura","ANCA-associated vasculitis","Thrombocytopenic purpura","Cryoglobulinaemia","Erythema nodosum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecryoglobulinaemia\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is strongly associated with hepatitis C infection, which the patient has. The presentation of palpable purpura on the lower extremities and fatigue is typical for cryoglobulinaemia. The skin biopsy findings of small vessel inflammation with immune deposits are characteristic of this condition. Cryoglobulinaemia occurs when cryoglobulins (proteins that precipitate at low temperatures) form immune complexes that deposit in small blood vessels, leading to vasculitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHenoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura\u003C/strong\u003E (HSP) typically affects children and young adults, and is characterized by palpable purpura, arthritis, abdominal pain, and renal involvement. While the rash can be similar, the patient\u0027s age and lack of other typical HSP symptoms make this diagnosis less likely. Skin biopsy would typically show leukocytoclastic vasculitis with IgA deposits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EANCA-associated vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a similar rash, but it\u0027s not typically associated with hepatitis C. Additionally, ANCA-associated vasculitis often involves the upper and lower respiratory tract and kidneys, which are not mentioned in this case. Biopsy in ANCA-associated vasculitis would show a granulomatous or necrotizing vasculitis without immune deposits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a petechial rash, but it would also be associated with a low platelet count and spontaneous bleeding not mentioned in the step. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythema nodosum\u003C/strong\u003E may be associated with hepatitis C (in addition to inflammatory disorders such as inflammatory bowel disease), it typically presents with painful, red nodules on the shins, distinct from the lesions described in this case. Skin biopsy would show septal panniculitis without vasculitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECryoglobulinaemia is an important extrahepatic manifestation of hepatitis C infection, although its incidence is decreasing with the widespread uptake of direct-acting antivirals. The diagnosis is confirmed by detecting elevated serum cryoglobulins, which would be the next appropriate test in this case. Treatment typically involves addressing the underlying hepatitis C infection and may include immunosuppressive therapy in severe cases. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cryoglobulinaemia is an important extrahepatic manifestation of hepatitis C infection.","Cryoglobulinaemia typically presents with palpable purpura on the lower extremities and fatigue.","Diagnosis of cryoglobulinaemia is confirmed by elevated serum cryoglobulins and characteristic skin biopsy findings."],"references":["Desbois AC, Cacoub P, Saadoun D. Cryoglobulinemia: An update in 2019. Joint Bone Spine. 2019 Nov;86(6):707-713."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37211"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"599"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}